   INDIA, JAN 12-13, 2024},
Abstract = {The Industrial Revolution 1.0 thrived in eighteenth century with
   factories and machines such as steam engines leading to mechanization of
   production. The Industrial Revolution 2.0 was propelled by electricity-
   and oil-based power in nineteenth century for mass production. The
   Industrial Revolution 3.0 was cultivated in the twentieth century
   through Electronics and Information and Communication Technologies for
   automatic production. The current phase of Industrial Revolution 4.0 in
   twenty-first century is built over the Industrial Revolution 3.0; but
   indeed is distinct from it due to its exponential growth, scope and
   impact across different sectors and industries in the Anthropocene age
   or era of humans. The Industrial Revolution 4.0 is led by technologies
   with `Digital Intelligence' such as `Internet of things', `Artificial
   Intelligence', `Cloud Computing', `Quantum Computing', etc. Within the
   artificial intelligence (AI), the generative artificial intelligence
   (GAI) with its scale, scope, and complexity will progress toward a
   period that humankind has never experienced before. Parallel to the
   development of the digitally intelligent machines have emerged a new set
   of generational human rights which can also be called as `Digital
   Rights' to safeguard our human rights in digital space. Right to be
   forgotten (RTBF) is one such emerging legal and digital right in civil,
   criminal, and tortious justice system. This research paper discusses the
   role of RTBF in the realm of one the prominent `Digitally Intelligent'
   technology-GAI and discusses the conflicts of interests and rights
   arising between RTBF and GAI models.},
