   {[}Anonymous], 114 The tensions between China, Japan, the U.S., and England become significantly compounded when considered in combination with the socio-political events at the end of the 19th century and at the beginning of the 20th century. When Fenollosa visited Japan in 1896, the First Sino-Japanese War had just ended a year ago, in April 1895, which for China revealed how corrupt and ineffective the government and policies were under the Qing Dynasty. Japan, on the other hand, had displayed its superior military tactics that it adopted from the West. By order of the Treaty of Shimonoseki, the Qing Empire ceded Liaodong Peninsula, Taiwan, and the Penghu Islands to Japan. The Empire also paid 200 million taels of silver to Japan for war reparations. After the war, China grew at risk of being divided and colonized by other Western powers as well as Russia, and the new imperialism that stemmed from Chinas defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War established the Open Door Policy by September 1899, only a few months after Fenollosas return to Japan earlier that February. This policy, to which the Chinese vehemently opposed, eventually contributed to the nationalism that fueled the Boxcar Rebellion in between 1899 and 1901. In addition to a number of long-term consequences of the rebellion, two worth mentioning here include: 1) the rebellion signaled the ceding of Europes interference with Chinese affairs (the Japanese would replace the European powers as the dominant power in the East; and 2) it marked a crucial shift in the U.S. presidential powers that would use military force against non-governmental organizations without Congressional authorization (President McKinley sent five thousand U.S. troops to assuage the rebellion). Japan, meanwhile, invaded Taiwan shortly after the Treaty of Shimonoseki, sustaining heavy casualties during the months between May and October in 1895. By 1915, the Qing Dynasty had been overthrown during the Wuchang Rising in Wuhan, and the Republic of China (1912-1949) had been created as the provisional government. Sun Yat-sen was announced as President, but for less than a year before Yuan Shikai, commander of the New Army and Prime Minister under the Qing Government, took his place. In 1915, Yuan declared himself emperor, and his short-lived attempt at a monarchy was upset by various rebellions, for which he abdicated his position in 1916. In Japan, the Meiji government experienced a quick transition towards an industrialized economy, and this economic stability, coupled with Japans increasing (and healthier, longer-living population), saw Japan develop into a strong democratic institution whose international power was growing by the Taisho period. The relationships between China and Japan during this period grew byzantine. In 1914, Chinas Parliament was formally dissolved, and Yuan produced a ``constitutional compact{''} that essentially replaced Chinas provisional constitution, which gave Yuan, as president, virtually unlimited powers over Chinas military, finances, foreign policy, and the rights of the Chinese citizens. Yuan would justify these reforms by stating that representative democracy had been proven inefficient by political infighting. Furthermore, Japan issued China the Twenty-One Demands on January 8, 1915, which would extend Japanese control over Manchuria, and it would give the Japanese control over the Chinese economy. The result of these demands deleteriously influenced Japans relationship not just with China (the Chinese boycotted Japanese exports, which fell by 40\%), but also with the U.S. and Britain, both of whom saw the move as a domineering approach to diplomacy. The two western countries would also reevaluate their connection to the Japanese after the demands, which retroactively affected Japans ties with Britain, especially in light that the former had signed an important military alliance with the latter earlier in the century., DOI DOI 10.1596/978-1-4648-0010-8CH1.
